The most substantial and, arguably, most contentious RAF undertaking during the war was the [strategic bombing](/Strategic_bombing) campaign waged against Germany by [Bomber Command](/RAF_Bomber_Command). While RAF bombing raids on Germany commenced almost immediately with the outbreak of hostilities, they were largely ineffectual in the early stages. It was only later, particularly under the relentless and controversial leadership of [Air Chief Marshal](/Air_chief_marshal) [Arthur Travers Harris](/Arthur_Travers_Harris), that these attacks escalated in scale and devastating impact, commencing in early 1943. This shift was facilitated by crucial advancements in technology and the availability of larger numbers of more capable aircraft. The RAF largely adopted night-time [area bombing](/Area_bombing) tactics, targeting German cities such as [Hamburg](/Bombing_of_Hamburg_in_World_War_II) and [Dresden](/Bombing_of_Dresden), aiming to de-house and de-moralize the civilian population and cripple industrial output. While area bombing constituted the vast majority of Bomber Command's campaign, driven largely by Harris's conviction, the RAF also developed highly specialized precision bombing techniques for specific, high-value operations. Notable examples include the audacious ["Dambusters" raid](/Operation_Chastise) executed by [No. 617 Squadron](/No._617_Squadron_RAF), which targeted German dams, and the daring Amiens prison raid, famously known as [Operation Jericho](/Operation_Jericho). These operations, while smaller in scale, demonstrated a different facet of aerial offensive capabilities.

### Cold War era

*   Further information: [Cold War](/Cold_War)
*   Main article: [Structure of the Royal Air Force in 1989](/Structure_of_the_Royal_Air_Force_in_1989)

The cessation of the [Second World War](/Second_World_War) brought not peace, but a new kind of global tension, and with it, significant re-organisation for the RAF. The rapid technological advancements in air warfare, particularly the advent of jet fighters and bombers, necessitated a complete re-evaluation of doctrine and equipment. In the nascent stages of the [Cold War](/Cold_War), one of the RAF's earliest and most critical major operations was its participation in the [Berlin Airlift](/Berlin_Airlift), codenamed Operation Plainfire. From 26 June 1948 until the Soviet blockade of the city was finally lifted on 12 May 1949, the RAF contributed a substantial 17% of the total supplies delivered. This monumental logistical effort saw [Avro Yorks](/Avro_York) and [Douglas Dakotas](/Douglas_Dakota) ferrying provisions into [Gatow Airport](/Gatow_Airport), while [Short Sunderlands](/Short_Sunderland) made their dramatic landings on the waters of Lake Havel. A stark demonstration of air power's utility beyond combat.

The RAF also found itself embroiled in its first post-war engagements during the complex [1948 Arab–Israeli War](/1948_Arab%E2%80%93Israeli_War). During the withdrawal from the former [Mandatory Palestine](/Mandatory_Palestine) in May 1948, British [Supermarine Spitfire FR.18s](/Supermarine_Spitfire) were forced to engage and shoot down four [Royal Egyptian Air Force](/Egyptian_Air_Force) Spitfire LF.9s after the REAF mistakenly attacked [RAF Ramat David](/Ramat_David_Airbase). Further, more challenging encounters with the newly formed [Israeli Air Force](/Israeli_Air_Force) resulted in the loss of a [de Havilland Mosquito PR.34](/De_Havilland_Mosquito) in November 1948, and four Spitfire FR.18s and a [Hawker Tempest F.6](/Hawker_Tempest) in January 1949. The post-war world, it seemed, offered little respite from conflict.

Before [Britain](/United_Kingdom) developed its own independent [nuclear weapons](/Nuclear_weapon) capability, the RAF was, for a period, equipped with American nuclear weapons under the rather prosaic designation of [Project E](/Project_E). However, following the successful development of its indigenous arsenal, the British Government made a momentous decision on 16 February 1960: to share the country's [nuclear deterrent](/Nuclear_weapons_and_the_United_Kingdom) between the RAF and the formidable submarines of the [Royal Navy](/Royal_Navy). Initially, the focus was squarely on the air force's strategic [V bomber](/V_bomber) fleet. These aircraft were first armed with conventional nuclear [gravity bombs](/Gravity_bomb), later upgraded to carry the more advanced [Blue Steel missile](/Blue_Steel_missile). This era of aerial nuclear deterrence, however, was finite. With the subsequent development of the Royal Navy's [Polaris submarines](/Polaris_(UK_nuclear_programme)), the mantle of strategic nuclear deterrence definitively passed to the navy's undersea fleet on 30 June 1969. The RAF's strategic nuclear role then diminished, transforming into a tactical one, utilizing [WE.177](/WE.177) gravity bombs. This tactical capability was sustained by the V bombers well into the 1980s and, rather remarkably, by the [Panavia Tornado GR1](/RAF_Tornado_GR1) until as late as 1998.

