For a significant portion of the [Cold War](/Cold_War), the RAF's paramount role was the staunch defence of [Western Europe](/Western_Europe) against the looming threat of a potential attack from the [Soviet Union](/Soviet_Union). This commitment saw numerous RAF [squadrons based in West Germany](/RAF_Germany), forming a critical forward defence line. The primary RAF bases in RAF(G) were [RAF Brüggen](/RAF_Br%C3%BCggen), [RAF Gutersloh](/RAF_G%C3%BCtersloh), [RAF Laarbruch](/RAF_Laarbruch), and [RAF Wildenrath](/RAF_Wildenrath), with the latter holding the unique distinction of being the sole air defence base within RAF(G). As the sun set on the [British Empire](/British_Empire), global operations were, perhaps inevitably, scaled back. This shift was concretely marked by the disbandment of [RAF Far East Air Force](/RAF_Far_East_Air_Force) on 31 October 1971.

Despite this contraction of global reach, the RAF remained actively engaged in numerous conflicts throughout the Cold War period, demonstrating a persistent, if reduced, expeditionary capability. In June 1948, the RAF initiated [Operation Firedog](/Operation_Firedog), a campaign against Malayan pro-independence fighters during the protracted [Malayan Emergency](/Malayan_Emergency). These operations, flying out of [RAF Tengah](/RAF_Tengah) and [RAF Butterworth](/RAF_Butterworth), continued for a remarkable 12 years, until 1960. The RAF's involvement in the [Korean War](/Korean_War) was, by contrast, relatively minor, primarily involving [flying boats](/Flying_boat) in reconnaissance and transport roles. From 1953 to 1956, RAF Avro Lincoln squadrons were deployed to carry out anti-[Mau Mau](/Mau_Mau_rebellion) operations in [Kenya](/Kenya), utilizing its base at [RAF Eastleigh](/RAF_Eastleigh). The [Suez Crisis](/Suez_Crisis) in 1956 saw a substantial RAF role, with aircraft operating from [RAF Akrotiri](/RAF_Akrotiri) and [RAF Nicosia](/RAF_Nicosia) on [Cyprus](/Cyprus), and [RAF Luqa](/RAF_Luqa) and [RAF Hal Far](/RAF_Hal_Far) on [Malta](/Malta), as part of [Operation Musketeer](/Operation_Musketeer_(1956)). It was during this conflict that the RAF suffered its most recent loss to an enemy aircraft, when an [English Electric Canberra PR7](/English_Electric_Canberra) was shot down over [Syria](/Syria).

In 1957, the RAF was heavily involved in the [Jebel Akhdar War](/Jebel_Akhdar_War) in Oman, deploying both [de Havilland Venom](/De_Havilland_Venom) and [Avro Shackleton](/Avro_Shackleton) aircraft. Between July and December 1958, the RAF executed 1,635 raids, dropping 1,094 tons of bombs and firing 900 rockets, targeting insurgents, mountain villages, and critical water channels in a conflict that largely remained under the international radar. The [Konfrontasi](/Konfrontasi) with Indonesia in the early 1960s also saw RAF aircraft deployed, though a delicate balance of diplomacy and a selective disregard for certain events by both sides prevented it from escalating into a full-scale war. The RAF played a significant role in the [Aden Emergency](/Aden_Emergency) between 1963 and 1967. [Hawker Hunter FGA.9s](/Hawker_Hunter), based at [RAF Khormaksar](/RAF_Khormaksar) in Aden, were frequently called upon by the [British Army](/British_Army) to provide [close air support](/Close_air_support), striking rebel positions. The [Radfan Campaign](/Radfan_Campaign) (Operation Nutcracker) in early 1964 successfully suppressed the immediate revolt in Radfan, but it did little to quell the broader insurgency, ultimately leading to the British withdrawal from Aden in November 1967.

One of the largest and most publicly significant actions undertaken by the RAF during the Cold War was the aerial campaign during the 1982 [Falklands War](/Falklands_War). In this conflict, the RAF operated in close coordination with the [Fleet Air Arm](/Fleet_Air_Arm) of the [Royal Navy](/Royal_Navy). RAF aircraft were primarily deployed from the strategically vital mid-Atlantic outpost of [RAF Ascension Island](/RAF_Ascension_Island). A specific detachment from [No. 1 Squadron](/No._1_Squadron_RAF) was also embedded with the Royal Navy, flying operations from the aircraft carrier HMS Hermes. Remarkably, RAF pilots also flew missions utilizing the Royal Navy's [Sea Harriers](/Sea_Harrier) in the critical air-to-air combat role, with [Flight Lieutenant](/Flight_lieutenant) Dave Morgan achieving distinction as the highest-scoring pilot of the war. Following the British victory, the RAF maintained a substantial presence in the [South Atlantic](/South_Atlantic) to provide continuous air defence for the [Falkland Islands](/Falkland_Islands). This included the stationing of [McDonnell Douglas Phantom FGR2s](/McDonnell_Douglas_Phantom_in_UK_service) at [RAF Mount Pleasant](/RAF_Mount_Pleasant), a new base constructed in 1984 to support these operations.

### Post-Cold War

<figure>
<img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d4/Panavia_Tornado_GR4_at_RIAT_2016.jpg/320px-Panavia_Tornado_GR4_at_RIAT_2016.jpg" alt="The Tornado played an integral part in RAF operations from 1991 until its retirement in 2019" />
<figcaption>The [Tornado](/Panavia_Tornado) played an integral part in RAF operations from 1991 until its retirement in 2019</figcaption>
</figure>

With the rather abrupt conclusion of the [Cold War](/Cold_War) and the subsequent dissolution of the [Soviet Union](/Soviet_Union), the [Royal Air Force](/Royal_Air_Force)'s strategic focus predictably shifted. The emphasis returned to a doctrine of [expeditionary air power](/Expeditionary_warfare), a more agile and globally deployable force capable of responding to diverse threats far from home. Since 1990, the RAF has been continuously engaged in a series of significant large-scale operations. These include its involvement in the 1991 [Gulf War](/Gulf_War), the 1999 [Kosovo War](/Kosovo_War), the protracted 2001 [War in Afghanistan](/War_in_Afghanistan_(2001%E2%80%93present)), the [2003 invasion](/2003_invasion_of_Iraq) and subsequent [war in Iraq](/Iraq_War), the 2011 [intervention in Libya](/2011_military_intervention_in_Libya), and, from 2014 onwards, a sustained role in the [war against the Islamic State](/War_against_the_Islamic_State). A rather relentless schedule for a force that supposedly wants to be "left alone."

The RAF, ever keen to embrace new methods of projecting power (or perhaps just reduce human risk), began conducting [Remotely-piloted Air System (RPAS)](/Unmanned_aerial_vehicle) operations in 2004. This initiative saw [No. 1115 Flight](/No._1115_Flight_RAF) carrying out missions in Afghanistan and Iraq with the [General Atomics MQ-1 Predator](/General_Atomics_MQ-1_Predator). Initially, RAF personnel were embedded directly with the [United States Air Force](/United_States_Air_Force) to gain experience. However, the RAF soon established its own dedicated RPAS squadron in 2007, when [No. 39 Squadron](/No._39_Squadron_RAF) was reactivated as a [General Atomics MQ-9A Reaper](/General_Atomics_MQ-9_Reaper) unit, operating from [Creech AFB](/Creech_Air_Force_Base), Nevada, a rather distant outpost for a British squadron.

The RAF's 90th anniversary, a quaint milestone for an organization that has seen so much, was commemorated on 1 April 2008. The occasion was marked by a ceremonial flypast of the RAF's Aerobatic Display Team, the [Red Arrows](/Red_Arrows), accompanied by four formidable [Eurofighter Typhoons](/Eurofighter_Typhoon). This aerial spectacle traced a precise line along the [River Thames](/Thames), passing iconic London landmarks from just south of [London City Airport](/London_City_Airport) to Tower Bridge, the [London Eye](/London_Eye), the [RAF Memorial](/RAF_Memorial), and culminating at 13:00 over the [Ministry of Defence building](/Ministry_of_Defence_Main_Building). A grand display, designed to remind everyone of their continued existence, I suppose.

Since the end of the Cold War, the RAF has been subjected to no fewer than four major defence reviews: the 1990 [Options for Change](/Options_for_Change), the 1998 [Strategic Defence Review](/Strategic_Defence_Review_(1998)), the 2003 [Delivering Security in a Changing World](/Delivering_Security_in_a_Changing_World), and the 2010 [Strategic Defence and Security Review](/Strategic_Defence_and_Security_Review_2010) (SDSR). Predictably, all four of these reviews have consistently led to steady reductions in both manpower and the number of aircraft, particularly fast-jets, the very symbols of air power. As a direct consequence of the 2010 SDSR, the [BAE Systems Nimrod MRA4](/BAE_Systems_Nimrod_MRA4) maritime patrol aircraft program was unceremoniously cancelled due to persistent overspending and missed deadlines. Further reductions included a cut of 5,000 personnel, bringing the trained strength down to 33,000, and the premature retirement of the [Joint Force Harrier](/Joint_Force_Harrier) aircraft, specifically the [BAE Harrier GR7/GR9](/BAE_Harrier_II).

