### Air Command

The administrative and operational command of the RAF, a task surely as complex as threading a needle in a hurricane, is formally delegated by the [Air Force Board](/Air_Force_Board) to [Headquarters Air Command](/RAF_Air_Command). This critical nerve centre is strategically located at [RAF High Wycombe](/RAF_High_Wycombe) in [Buckinghamshire](/Buckinghamshire). Air Command itself was an entity born of consolidation, formed on 1 April 2007, through the merger of two previously distinct commands: [RAF Strike Command](/RAF_Strike_Command) and [RAF Personnel and Training Command](/RAF_Personnel_and_Training_Command). The result was a single, comprehensive command structure overseeing the entirety of the RAF, all under the direct leadership of the [Chief of the Air Staff](/Chief_of_the_Air_Staff_(United_Kingdom)). Through its various subordinate [groups](/Group_(military_unit)), Air Command meticulously oversees the entire spectrum of RAF aircraft and operations.

A more recent addition to this organizational chart is the [United Kingdom Space Command](/United_Kingdom_Space_Command) (UKSC), which was established on 1 April 2021, under the command of Air Vice-Marshal [Paul Godfrey](/Paul_Godfrey_(RAF_officer)). While technically a [joint](/Joint_warfare) command, it is strategically positioned "under the Royal Air Force," indicating a clear hierarchy. Air Vice-Marshal Godfrey holds a rank equivalent to the commanders of Nos. 1, 2, 11, and 22 Groups, signifying its importance within the broader structure. This new command has a rather expansive remit, encompassing "responsibility for not just operations, but also generating, training and growing the force, and also owning the money and putting all the programmatic rigour into delivering new capabilities." A rather ambitious portfolio, for sure. The UKSC headquarters is conveniently co-located with Air Command at [RAF High Wycombe](/RAF_High_Wycombe), ensuring a seamless integration of terrestrial and orbital ambitions.

### Groups

*   Main article: [List of Royal Air Force groups](/List_of_Royal_Air_Force_groups)

[Groups](/Group_(military_aviation_unit)) serve as the essential subdivisions of operational commands, each bearing responsibility for specific types of capabilities or for conducting operations within defined geographical areas. A necessary compartmentalization, to avoid utter chaos. There are currently five such groups operating under the overarching authority of [Air Command](/RAF_Air_Command). Of these, four are functionally oriented, focusing on distinct aspects of air power, while one maintains a more geographically concentrated mandate.

**No. 1 Group (Air Combat)**

[No. 1 Group](/No._1_Group_RAF) bears the unenviable burden of overseeing all combat aircraft, a responsibility that encompasses both the potent [Lightning Force](/Lightning_Force_HQ) and the versatile [Typhoon](/Eurofighter_Typhoon) Force. Furthermore, it is entrusted with the RAF's critical [intelligence, surveillance, target acquisition, and reconnaissance](/Intelligence,_surveillance,_target_acquisition,_and_reconnaissance) (ISTAR) capabilities. Its operational control extends over key stations such as [RAF Coningsby](/RAF_Coningsby) and [RAF Waddington](/RAF_Waddington) in Lincolnshire, [RAF Lossiemouth](/RAF_Lossiemouth) in Moray, and [RAF Marham](/RAF_Marham) in Norfolk. The group's primary workhorse, the [Eurofighter Typhoon FGR4](/Eurofighter_Typhoon_variants) aircraft, is tasked with the perpetual vigilance of protecting UK and NATO airspace, maintaining a continuous [Quick Reaction Alert](/Quick_Reaction_Alert) capability—a constant state of readiness for the unexpected.

**No. 2 Group (Air Combat Support)**

[No. 2 Group](/No._2_Group_RAF) is the operational backbone, controlling the vital Air Mobility Force. This force is responsible for providing [strategic and tactical airlift](/Airlift), essential [air-to-air refuelling](/Aerial_refueling) (a rather complex aerial ballet), and command support air transport (CSAT) for senior officials. Beyond these aerial logistics, the group also holds responsibility for the [RAF Medical Services](/RAF_Medical_Services), the comprehensive RAF Support Force (which includes the RAF's engineering, logistics, intelligence, signals, musical, and mountain rescue assets), the RAF's Combat and Readiness Force (comprising the formidable [RAF Regiment](/RAF_Regiment)), and the Air Security Force (which includes the [RAF Police](/Royal_Air_Force_Police)). Its domain extends across stations such as [RAF Benson](/RAF_Benson) and [RAF Brize Norton](/RAF_Brize_Norton) in Oxfordshire, [RAF Henlow](/RAF_Henlow) in Bedfordshire, [RAF Honington](/RAF_Honington) in Suffolk, [RAF Odiham](/RAF_Odiham) in Hampshire, and [RAF Northolt](/RAF_Northolt) in West London. A rather diverse and demanding portfolio, ensuring everything runs smoothly, or at least, doesn't crash and burn.

**No. 11 Group (Multi-domain operations)**

[No. 11 Group](/No._11_Group_RAF) is tasked with the increasingly complex integration of operations across the [air](/Aerial_warfare), [cyber](/Cyberwarfare), and [space](/Space_warfare) domains, a rather modern challenge, while simultaneously responding to the ever-evolving spectrum of threats. This group encompasses the RAF's Battlespace Management Force, which is responsible for controlling the intricate UK Air Surveillance and Control System (ASACS). Its operational footprint includes stations such as [RAF Boulmer](/RAF_Boulmer) in Northumberland, [RAF Fylingdales](/RAF_Fylingdales) in North Yorkshire, and [RAF Spadeadam](/RAF_Spadeadam) in Cumbria. A rather invisible but crucial role, monitoring the unseen.

**No. 22 Group (Training)**

[No. 22 Group](/No._22_Group_RAF) bears the fundamental responsibility for supplying qualified and skilled personnel to the RAF, a perpetual and essential undertaking. It provides both flying and non-flying training to all three branches of the [British armed services](/British_Armed_Forces). This group is the ultimate beneficiary of the [UK Military Flying Training System](/UK_Military_Flying_Training_System), a comprehensive program delivered by the civilian contractor [Ascent Flight Training](/Ascent_Flight_Training). Its oversight extends to stations like [RAF College Cranwell](/RAF_Cranwell) in Lincolnshire, [RAF Cosford](/RAF_Cosford) and [RAF Shawbury](/RAF_Shawbury) in Shropshire, [RAF Halton](/RAF_Halton) in Buckinghamshire, [MOD St Athan](/MOD_St_Athan) in the Vale of Glamorgan, [RAF St Mawgan](/RAF_St_Mawgan) in Cornwall, and [RAF Valley](/RAF_Valley) on Anglesey. Furthermore, [No. 22 Group](/No._22_Group_RAF) is also responsible for managing the [Royal Air Force Air Cadets](/Royal_Air_Force_Air_Cadets), nurturing the next generation of aviators and support staff. A rather extensive pipeline for human resources.

### Stations

*   Main article: [Royal Air Force station](/Royal_Air_Force_station)
*   See also: [List of Royal Air Force stations](/List_of_Royal_Air_Force_stations) and [List of former Royal Air Force stations](/List_of_former_Royal_Air_Force_stations)

<figure>
<img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d4/United_Kingdom_relief_location_map.jpg/320px-United_Kingdom_relief_location_map.jpg" alt="Map of the Royal Air Force's main stations." />
<figcaption>Map of the [Royal Air Force](/Royal_Air_Force)'s main stations.<br />&#160;Front-line flying station<br />&#160;Training station<br />&#160;Battlespace management<br />&#160;Support station</figcaption>
</figure>

An RAF station, the fundamental geographical unit of the service, is typically subordinate to a larger [group](/Group_(military_unit)) and operates under the command of a [group captain](/Group_captain). Each station generally accommodates several flying and non-flying [squadrons](/List_of_Royal_Air_Force_aircraft_squadrons) or specialized [units](/List_of_Royal_Air_Force_units_%26_establishments), all of which are supported by various administrative and logistical wings. A self-contained ecosystem, designed for efficiency, or at least, self-preservation.

#### United Kingdom

Front-line flying operations, the sharp end of the spear, are concentrated at eight key stations across the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom):

*   [RAF Coningsby](/RAF_Coningsby), [RAF Marham](/RAF_Marham), and [RAF Lossiemouth](/RAF_Lossiemouth) serve as the primary hubs for Air Combat operations.
*   [RAF Waddington](/RAF_Waddington) is dedicated to [ISTAR](/ISTAR) (Intelligence, Surveillance, Target Acquisition, and Reconnaissance) activities.
*   [RAF Brize Norton](/RAF_Brize_Norton) and [RAF Northolt](/RAF_Northolt) manage the crucial Air Transport roles.
*   [RAF Benson](/RAF_Benson) and [RAF Odiham](/RAF_Odiham) host the Support Helicopter Force, operating under the tri-service [Joint Aviation Command](/Joint_Aviation_Command).

Flying training, the arduous process of turning raw recruits into skilled aviators, takes place at [RAF Barkston Heath](/RAF_Barkston_Heath), [RAF College Cranwell](/RAF_College_Cranwell), [RAF Shawbury](/RAF_Shawbury), and [RAF Valley](/RAF_Valley). Each of these stations forms an integral part of the [UK Military Flying Training System](/UK_Military_Flying_Training_System), a comprehensive program dedicated to training aircrew for all three UK armed services. Specialist ground crew training, equally vital but far less glamorous, is concentrated at [RAF Cosford](/RAF_Cosford), [RAF St Mawgan](/RAF_St_Mawgan), and [MOD St. Athan](/MOD_St_Athan).

Operations are further supported by a multitude of other flying and non-flying stations. Activity is particularly focused at [RAF Honington](/RAF_Honington), which meticulously coordinates [Force Protection](/RAF_Force_Protection_Force_Headquarters) efforts, and at [RAF Leeming](/RAF_Leeming) & [RAF Wittering](/RAF_Wittering), which fulfil critical support enabler roles.

A dedicated [Control and Reporting Centre](/Control_and_Reporting_Centre) (CRC) at [RAF Boulmer](/RAF_Boulmer) is tasked with the complex mission of compiling a [Recognised Air Picture](/Recognized_Air_Picture) of UK airspace and providing tactical control for the [Quick Reaction Alert Force](/Quick_Reaction_Alert). To achieve this round-the-clock vigilance, Boulmer is supported by an extensive network of eight Remote [Radar](/Radar) Heads (RRHs) strategically dispersed across the length and breadth of the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom). A rather intricate dance of technology and human vigilance.

#### Overseas

The [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom) maintains permanent military airfields, rather grandly known as Permanent Joint Operating Bases, in four distinct [British Overseas Territories](/British_Overseas_Territories). These strategically located bases serve a dual purpose: they contribute directly to the physical defence and the assertion of sovereignty over these territories, and they simultaneously enable the UK to conduct vital [expeditionary military operations](/Expeditionary_warfare) far from home. While command and oversight of these bases fall under the purview of [Strategic Command](/Strategic_Command_(United_Kingdom)), the airfield elements themselves are, somewhat confusingly, still referred to as RAF stations. A bureaucratic quirk, perhaps.

*   [RAF Akrotiri](/RAF_Akrotiri) (within the [Sovereign Base Areas of Akrotiri and Dhekelia](/Sovereign_Base_Areas_of_Akrotiri_and_Dhekelia), [Cyprus](/Cyprus))
*   [RAF Ascension Island](/RAF_Ascension_Island) (part of [Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cuhna](/Saint_Helena,_Ascension_and_Tristan_da_Cunha))
*   [RAF Mount Pleasant](/RAF_Mount_Pleasant) (in the [Falkland Islands](/Falkland_Islands))
*   [RAF Gibraltar](/RAF_Gibraltar) (on [Gibraltar](/Gibraltar))

Beyond these permanent bases, four RAF [squadrons](/List_of_Royal_Air_Force_aircraft_squadrons) are stationed overseas, demonstrating a persistent global reach. [No. 17 Test and Evaluation Squadron](/No._17_Squadron_RAF) is strategically located at [Edwards Air Force Base](/Edwards_Air_Force_Base), California, in the [United States](/United_States), where it works in close cooperation with the [U.S. Air Force](/United_States_Air_Force) on the ongoing development of the [Lockheed Martin F-35B Lightning](/Lockheed_Martin_F-35_Lightning_II). A rather convenient arrangement. [No. 80 Squadron](/No._80_Squadron_RAF) is an integral part of the Australia, Canada and United Kingdom Reprogramming Laboratory (ACURL) at [Eglin Air Force Base](/Eglin_Air_Force_Base), Florida, tasked with the intricate work of compiling and testing the Mission Data File Sets (MDFS) for the F-35. [No. 84 Squadron](/No._84_Squadron_RAF) is based at [RAF Akrotiri](/RAF_Akrotiri) in [Cyprus](/Cyprus), fulfilling a crucial search and rescue role. Finally, [No. 230 Squadron](/No._230_Squadron_RAF) is stationed at [Medicina Lines](/British_Forces_Brunei) in Brunei, maintaining a presence in Southeast Asia.

### Squadrons

*   Main article: [List of Royal Air Force aircraft squadrons](/List_of_Royal_Air_Force_aircraft_squadrons)

A flying squadron, the very embodiment of an aircraft unit, is fundamentally responsible for executing the primary operational tasks of the [Royal Air Force](/Royal_Air_Force). RAF squadrons, much like the regiments of the [British Army](/British_Army), possess rich histories and deeply ingrained traditions that often stretch back to their very formation, irrespective of their current base or the specific aircraft they happen to be operating. This continuity provides a sense of identity, a thread through time. They are, in recognition of meritorious service, eligible to be awarded [standards](/Flag) and prestigious [battle honours](/RAF_battle_honours). Most flying squadrons are typically commanded by a [wing commander](/Wing_commander) and, in the case of a fast-jet squadron, are generally equipped with a complement of approximately twelve aircraft. A relatively small, but potent, fighting force.

### Flights

*   See also: [List of Royal Air Force aircraft independent flights](/List_of_Royal_Air_Force_aircraft_independent_flights)

