## Aircraft

*   Further information: [List of aircraft of the RAF](/List_of_aircraft_of_the_RAF) and [List of active United Kingdom military aircraft](/List_of_active_United_Kingdom_military_aircraft)

### Air combat

#### Typhoon

<figure>
<img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f8/Eurofighter_Typhoon_FGR4_at_RIAT_2017.jpg/320px-Eurofighter_Typhoon_FGR4_at_RIAT_2017.jpg" alt="Typhoon" />
<figcaption>[Typhoon FGR4](/Eurofighter_Typhoon)</figcaption>
</figure>

The [Eurofighter Typhoon FGR4](/Eurofighter_Typhoon) currently serves as the [Royal Air Force](/Royal_Air_Force)'s primary multi-role air defence and ground attack fighter aircraft. A rather versatile machine, expected to perform numerous demanding tasks, particularly since the retirement of the dedicated air defence [Panavia Tornado F3](/Panavia_Tornado_ADV) in late March 2011. With the successful completion of the 'Project Centurion' upgrades, the Typhoon FGR4 effectively absorbed the ground attack responsibilities that were previously handled by the [Panavia Tornado GR4](/Panavia_Tornado_GR4), which itself was retired on 1 April 2019. This consolidation of roles means the Typhoon is now tasked with the perpetual defense of UK airspace, a rather critical responsibility, while also frequently deploying in support of [NATO](/NATO) air defence missions in various theatres: the Baltic (under Operation Azotize), the Black Sea (Operation Biloxi), Iceland ([Icelandic Air Policing](/Icelandic_Air_Policing)), and Poland (Operation Chessman). A busy life for a fighter jet.

The RAF currently maintains seven front-line Typhoon squadrons, supported by an [Operational Conversion Unit](/Operational_Conversion_Unit) (OCU) and an [Operational Evaluation Unit](/Operational_Evaluation_Unit) (OEU). These include [No. 3 (Fighter) Squadron](/No._3_Squadron_RAF), [No. XI (F) Squadron](/No._11_Squadron_RAF), [No. 12 Squadron](/No._12_Squadron_RAF) (a unique joint RAF / [Qatar Air Force](/Qatar_Air_Force) unit), [No. 29 Squadron](/No._29_Squadron_RAF) (the OCU), and [No. 41 Test and Evaluation Squadron](/No._41_Squadron_RAF) (the OEU), all based at [RAF Coningsby](/RAF_Coningsby). Additionally, [No. 1 (F) Squadron](/1_Squadron_RAF), [No. II (Army Cooperation) Squadron](/No._2_Squadron_RAF), [No. 6 Squadron](/No._6_Squadron_RAF), and [No. IX (Bomber) Squadron](/No._9_Squadron_RAF) are stationed at [RAF Lossiemouth](/RAF_Lossiemouth). Furthermore, a detachment of four Typhoons – rather poetically named Faith, Hope, Charity, and Desperation (a nod to the defenders of [Malta](/Malta) in WWII) – are permanently based at [RAF Mount Pleasant](/RAF_Mount_Pleasant) on the [Falkland Islands](/Falkland_Islands), forming [No. 1435 Flight](/No._1435_Flight_RAF) and providing essential air defence. While there was initial talk of forming an eighth front-line Typhoon squadron, the [2021 Defence Command Paper](/Defence_in_a_Competitive_Age) announced the retirement of 24 Tranche 1 Typhoons by 2025, reaffirming the commitment to seven front-line squadrons. On 31 March 2025, the majority of the Tranche 1 Typhoons were indeed withdrawn from service, with the remaining four continuing as part of No. 1435 Flight until 2027.

The Typhoon made its combat debut in support of [Operation Ellamy](/Operation_Ellamy) in 2011, and has been a continuous presence in [Operation Shader](/Operation_Shader) since December 2015. More recently, Typhoons have also been actively supporting [Operation Poseidon Archer](/2024_missile_strikes_in_Yemen) since January 2024. The aircraft achieved its first air-to-air kill in December 2021, rather unceremoniously shooting down a small hostile drone near [Al-Tanf base](/Al-Tanf_(U.S._military_base)), [Syria](/Syria), using an [ASRAAM](/ASRAAM) missile. A testament to its capabilities, even against the smallest of threats.

#### Lightning

<figure>
<img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4b/An_F-35B_Lightning_II_jet_takes_off_from_HMS_Queen_Elizabeth.jpg/320px-An_F-35B_Lightning_II_jet_takes_off_from_HMS_Queen_Elizabeth.jpg" alt="F-35B Lightning" />
<figcaption>[F-35B Lightning](/Lockheed_Martin_F-35_Lightning_II)</figcaption>
</figure>

The [Lockheed Martin F-35 Lightning](/Lockheed_Martin_F-35_Lightning_II) is a single-seat, single-engine, all-weather [stealth](/Stealth_aircraft) [multirole combat aircraft](/Multirole_combat_aircraft). It is designed to perform a complex array of missions, including both [air superiority](/Air_superiority_fighter) and [strike](/Attack_aircraft), while also providing sophisticated [electronic warfare](/Electronic_warfare) and [intelligence, surveillance, and reconnaissance](/Intelligence,_surveillance,_and_reconnaissance) capabilities. The F-35B variant, with its impressive ability to perform [short take-offs and vertical-landings](/STOVL) (STOVL), is jointly operated by the [Royal Air Force](/Royal_Air_Force) and the [Fleet Air Arm](/Fleet_Air_Arm) (FAA) of the [Royal Navy](/Royal_Navy), who regularly deploy from the Royal Navy's two formidable Queen Elizabeth-class aircraft carriers. Furthermore, the F-35A, a variant without STOVL capabilities, is currently on order, specifically to enable the RAF to participate in [NATO's nuclear mission](/Nuclear_sharing).

Originally, a rather ambitious total of 138 F-35B Lightnings were planned for procurement. However, the [2021 Defence Command Paper](/Defence_in_a_Competitive_Age) revised this figure, committing instead to an increase in the fleet beyond the initial order of 48 aircraft. In June 2025, the second phase of the procurement plan was announced, confirming the purchase of 12 F-35As and an additional 17 F-35Bs, which will bring the total ordered fleet up to 75 jets. By August 2025, 40 F-35Bs had already been delivered to the RAF, though one, rather unfortunately, crashed in November 2021. The F-35B is projected to remain in service for a considerable period, with an out of service date (OSD) of 2069. A long-term investment, indeed.

The first RAF squadron to operate the F-35B was [No. 17 Test and Evaluation Squadron](/No._17_Squadron_RAF) at [Edwards AFB](/Edwards_Air_Force_Base), California, which accepted its first aircraft in 2014. [No. 617 (The Dambusters) Squadron](/No._617_Squadron_RAF) officially reformed on 18 April 2018, becoming the RAF's inaugural operational Lightning squadron. The initial four aircraft arrived at [RAF Marham](/RAF_Marham) from the [United States](/United_States) in June 2018, followed by a further five in August 2018. The Lightning fleet was declared combat ready in January 2019. The second UK-based F-35B squadron to be established was [No. 207 Squadron](/No._207_Squadron_RAF) on 1 August 2019, serving as the OCU for both RAF and [Royal Navy](/Royal_Navy) pilots. The second front-line F-35B squadron was [809 Naval Air Squadron](/809_Naval_Air_Squadron) (FAA), reformed on 8 December 2023, and, like its predecessors, is crewed by a mix of Royal Navy and RAF personnel.

At the [2025 NATO Summit](/2025_The_Hague_NATO_summit) in [The Hague](/The_Hague), Prime Minister [Keir Starmer](/Keir_Starmer) announced the UK's intention to acquire at least twelve nuclear-capable F-35As. This significant decision marks the return of a nuclear role for the RAF, a capability absent since 1998 when the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom) retired its [WE.177](/WE.177) bombs from service. According to the [Ministry of Defence](/Ministry_of_Defence_(United_Kingdom)), these F-35As will be based at [RAF Marham](/RAF_Marham) and will facilitate the establishment of a third front-line F-35 Lightning squadron. The OCU, [No. 207 Squadron](/No._207_Squadron_RAF), will utilize the F-35A in a training capacity for day-to-day operations, benefiting from their increased flight time and reduced maintenance requirements. These highly anticipated aircraft are planned for delivery by 2030.

### Intelligence, surveillance, target acquisition, and reconnaissance (ISTAR)

#### Shadow

Eight [Shadows](/Beechcraft_Super_King_Air) aircraft, comprising six Shadow R1+ and two Shadow R2 variants, are operated by [No. 14 Squadron](/No._14_Squadron_RAF) from [RAF Waddington](/RAF_Waddington). These aircraft are, in essence, King Air 350CERs that have undergone specialized conversion for the demanding [ISTAR](/ISTAR) role. The initial order for four Shadow R1s was placed in 2007, driven by an [Urgent Operational Requirement](/Urgent_Operational_Requirement), with their conversion to the ISTAR role commencing in 2009. A rapid response to an immediate need.

#### Protector

The General Atomics Protector RG1 was officially inducted into [Royal Air Force](/Royal_Air_Force) service on 17 June 2025, with [31 Squadron](/No._31_Squadron_RAF) beginning operational flying in late 2025. This advanced system is set to replace the legacy MQ-9A Reapers of XIII Squadron. On 5 October 2015, it was announced that the "Scavenger" programme, a rather evocative name, had been superseded by "Protector," a new requirement for a fleet of at least 20 [unmanned aerial vehicles](/Unmanned_aerial_vehicle). Just two days later, on 7 October 2015, it was revealed that the Protector would be a [certifiable](/Type_certificate) derivative of the [MQ-9B SkyGuardian](/MQ-9_Reaper), boasting enhanced range and endurance capabilities. In 2016, indications suggested that at least sixteen aircraft would be procured, with a potential maximum of twenty-six. In July 2018, a [General Atomics](/General_Atomics) US civil-registered SkyGuardian made a transatlantic flight from North Dakota to [RAF Fairford](/RAF_Fairford) for the [Royal International Air Tattoo](/Royal_International_Air_Tattoo), where it was temporarily adorned with RAF markings. In July 2020, the [Ministry of Defence](/Ministry_of_Defence_(United_Kingdom)) formalized a contract for three Protectors, with an option for an additional thirteen aircraft. The [2021 Defence Command Paper](/Defence_in_a_Competitive_Age) subsequently confirmed the order for 16 Protectors, despite the 2015 SDSR's original plans for over 20. The first Protector RG1 (PR009) was delivered to [RAF Waddington](/RAF_Waddington) in September 2023. [No. 31 Squadron](/No._31_Squadron_RAF) was reformed as the inaugural Protector squadron on 11 October 2023, a role it had been earmarked for since 2018. As of June 2025, ten Protector UAVs were in active service, with the remaining 6 aircraft anticipated for delivery by the close of the year. A steady progression into the era of autonomous aerial surveillance.

#### RC-135W Rivet Joint

Three [Boeing RC-135W Rivet Joints](/Boeing_RC-135) were acquired to replace the venerable [Hawker Siddeley Nimrod R1](/Hawker_Siddeley_Nimrod_R1) fleet in the critical [signals intelligence](/Signals_intelligence) role, under the rather descriptive "Airseeker Programme." These aircraft are operated by [No. 51 Squadron](/No._51_Squadron_RAF). The Nimrod fleet was finally retired in 2011, leaving a temporary capability gap during which RAF personnel co-manned aircraft of the [US Air Force](/United_States_Air_Force) until the three RC-135s entered service between 2014 and 2017. The aircraft themselves were originally [Boeing KC-135R Stratotanker](/Boeing_KC-135_Stratotanker) tankers, meticulously converted to the RC-135W standard. This conversion represented the most complex combined [Foreign Military Sales](/Foreign_Military_Sales) case and cooperative support arrangement that the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom) had undertaken with the [United States Air Force](/United_States_Air_Force) since the [Second World War](/Second_World_War). A rather intricate dance of international cooperation.

The Rivet Joint received its first operational deployment in August 2014, when it was dispatched to the Middle East to conduct missions over [Iraq](/Iraq) and [Syria](/Syria) as part of [Operation Shader](/Operation_Shader). The RC-135W's out-of-service date (OSD) is currently projected for 2035, indicating a sustained commitment to this vital intelligence platform.

#### Wedgetail

The [Royal Air Force](/Royal_Air_Force) is currently anticipating the initial delivery of three [E-7 Wedgetail](/Boeing_E-7_Wedgetail) Airborne Warning and Control Systems (AWACS) aircraft towards the end of 2025. These aircraft will be designated Wedgetail AEW1 and are slated to be operated by [8 Squadron](/8_Squadron_RAF) at [RAF Lossiemouth](/RAF_Lossiemouth), with an expected in-service date of early 2026. The Wedgetail is poised to provide crucial Airborne Early Warning and Control (AEW&C) capabilities, a critical component of modern air defence. It generates high-resolution radar data and seamlessly shares this information in real-time through its advanced communication links. A rather sophisticated eye in the sky, designed to provide unparalleled situational awareness.

#### Other ISTAR Units

Based at [RAF Waddington](/RAF_Waddington), [No. 54 Squadron](/No._54_Squadron_RAF) and [No. 56 Squadron](/No._56_Squadron_RAF) serve as the OCU (Operational Conversion Unit) and OEU (Operational Evaluation Unit) for the entire [ISTAR](/ISTAR) fleet, respectively. These units ensure that personnel are properly trained and that the capabilities of the fleet are continuously evaluated and optimized.

