### Helicopters

<figure>
<img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e0/Boeing_Chinook_HC6A_at_RAF_Odiham_2016.jpg/320px-Boeing_Chinook_HC6A_at_RAF_Odiham_2016.jpg" alt="Boeing Chinook HC6A" />
<figcaption>[Boeing Chinook HC6A](/Boeing_Chinook_(UK_variants))</figcaption>
</figure>

RAF helicopters provide invaluable support to the [British Army](/British_Army), primarily by facilitating the rapid movement of troops and essential equipment both to and around the battlefield. A vital, if often dangerous, logistical function. These rotary-wing assets are also deployed in a diverse array of other roles, including direct support for RAF ground units and providing heavy-lift capabilities for the [Royal Marines](/Royal_Marines). The support helicopters are strategically organized into the tri-service [Joint Aviation Command](/Joint_Aviation_Command) (JAC), a collaborative entity that also includes helicopters from the British Army and the [Royal Navy](/Royal_Navy). [No. 22 Squadron](/No._22_Squadron_RAF), based at [RAF Benson](/RAF_Benson), serves as the OEU (Operational Evaluation Unit) for JAC, ensuring the continuous assessment and optimization of helicopter operations.

#### Chinook HC5/HC6/HC6A

The formidable large twin-rotor [Boeing Chinook](/Boeing_Chinook_(UK_variants)) stands as the [Royal Air Force](/Royal_Air_Force)'s heavy-lift support helicopter, an indispensable asset for moving significant loads. Initially ordered in 1978, with subsequent orders placed in 1995, 2011, and a further order planned in 2018 (yet to be finalized), the Chinook fleet is operated by [No. 7 Squadron](/No._7_Squadron_RAF), [No. 18 (B) Squadron](/No._18_Squadron_RAF), and [No. 27 Squadron](/No._27_Squadron_RAF) at [RAF Odiham](/RAF_Odiham), alongside [No. 28 (AC) Squadron](/No._28_Squadron_RAF) (the Support Helicopter OCU) at [RAF Benson](/RAF_Benson). Since its first delivery in 1980, the Chinook has been a constant presence in numerous operations, demonstrating its versatility and resilience: the [Falklands War](/Falklands_War) (1982); [Operation Granby](/Operation_Granby) (1991); [Operation Engadine](/NATO_bombing_of_Yugoslavia) (1999); [Operation Barras](/Operation_Barras) (2000); [Operation Herrick](/Operation_Herrick) (2002–2014); [Operation Telic](/Operation_Telic) (2003–2011); [Operation Ruman](/Operation_RUMAN) (2017); and [Operation Newcombe](/Operation_Barkhane) (2018–2022). The current 54-strong fleet of Chinooks is projected to remain in service for a considerable period, with an out-of-service date (OSD) extending into the 2040s. A long and storied career for a workhorse helicopter.

### Training aircraft

*   Main article: [UK Military Flying Training System](/UK_Military_Flying_Training_System)

The [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom)'s military flying training has undergone a significant transformation, with its privatization implemented through a [public-private partnership](/Public%E2%80%93private_partnership) known as the [UK Military Flying Training System](/UK_Military_Flying_Training_System) (UKMFTS). Training services are now provided by [Ascent Flight Training](/Ascent_Flight_Training), a consortium formed by [Lockheed Martin](/Lockheed_Martin) and [Babcock International](/Babcock_International). New aircraft were strategically procured to bridge the training gap that existed between the older generation of [Grob Tutor T1](/Grob_G_115), [Short Tucano T1](/Short_Tucano), and [Beechcraft King Air T1](/Beechcraft_King_Air) aircraft, and the RAF's modern front-line aircraft. This modernization includes the incorporation of advanced systems and the ubiquitous [glass cockpits](/Glass_cockpit) found in contemporary military aircraft. The UKMFTS also places a far greater emphasis on [synthetic training](/Flight_simulator), utilizing advanced simulators to prepare aircrew for the complex realities of front-line operations, where such synthetic training is increasingly commonplace. A rather efficient, if somewhat sterile, approach to learning.

#### Initial training

The [Grob Tutor T1](/Grob_G_115) forms the backbone of fifteen [University Air Squadrons](/University_Air_Squadron), which offer university students the unique opportunity to undertake an RAF training syllabus. This includes achieving their first solo flight, alongside instruction in air navigation, aerobatics, and formation flying. These units are conveniently co-located with [Air Experience Flights](/Air_Experience_Flight), which share the same aircraft and facilities, providing introductory air experience flying to members of the [Air Training Corps](/Air_Training_Corps) and [Combined Cadet Force](/Combined_Cadet_Force). The Tutor is also flown by [No. 16 Squadron](/No._16_Squadron_RAF) and [No. 115 Squadron](/No._115_Squadron_RAF), both based at [RAF Wittering](/RAF_Wittering).

[Volunteer Gliding Squadrons](/Volunteer_Gliding_Squadron) also contribute to air experience flying for cadets, utilizing the [Grob Viking T1](/Grob_G103a_Twin_II) conventional glider. However, a rather inconvenient airworthiness issue in April 2014 led to the grounding of both the Viking fleet and the [Grob Vigilant T1](/Grob_G109) fleet for a two-year period, though Viking operations have since resumed. The Vigilant was, rather abruptly, withdrawn from service in May 2018, a year earlier than originally planned. A contract tender was subsequently initiated in February 2018 to replace this lost capability from 2022 onwards.

#### Elementary training

The [Grob Prefect T1](/Grob_G_120TP) was introduced into [Royal Air Force](/Royal_Air_Force) service in 2016, serving as its dedicated elementary trainer. The fleet, comprising 23 aircraft, is based at [RAF Cranwell](/RAF_Cranwell) and [RAF Barkston Heath](/RAF_Barkston_Heath) in Lincolnshire, where they are operated by [No. 57 Squadron](/No._57_Squadron_RAF). Upon successful completion of elementary training, aircrew are then streamed into specialized pathways: fast jet, multi-engine, or rotary training, depending on their aptitude and the needs of the service.

#### Basic fast jet training

Basic fast jet training is now provided on the [Beechcraft Texan T1](/Beechcraft_T-6_Texan_II), which superseded the Short Tucano T1 in November 2019. The Texan is a tandem-seat [turboprop](/Turboprop) aircraft, notable for its modern digital [glass cockpit](/Glass_cockpit). It is operated by [No. 72 (F) Squadron](/No._72_Squadron_RAF), based at [RAF Valley](/RAF_Valley) in [Anglesey](/Anglesey), providing crucial lead-in training for RAF and [Royal Navy](/Royal_Navy) fighter pilots prior to their advanced training on the [BAE Hawk T2](/BAE_Systems_Hawk). The initial two Texans were delivered in February 2018, and by December 2018, ten aircraft had arrived at RAF Valley. Four additional Texans were delivered on 3 November 2020, bolstering the training fleet.

#### Advanced fast jet training

The [BAE Hawk T2](/BAE_Systems_Hawk) is flown by [No. IV Squadron](/No._4_Squadron_RAF) and [No. XXV (F) Squadron](/No._25_Squadron_RAF), both based at [RAF Valley](/RAF_Valley). The latter squadron provides initial Advanced Fast Jet Training (AFJT), while pilots who successfully graduate to the former squadron delve into more complex tactical and weapons training. Following this advanced training, aircrew proceed to an [Operational Conversion Unit](/Operational_Conversion_Unit) (OCU) where they undergo specialized training to fly either the [Typhoon FGR4](/Eurofighter_Typhoon) ([No. 29 Squadron](/No._29_Squadron_RAF) at [RAF Coningsby](/RAF_Coningsby)) or the [F-35B Lightning](/Lockheed_Martin_F-35_Lightning_II) ([No. 207 Squadron](/No._207_Squadron_RAF) at [RAF Marham](/RAF_Marham)), preparing them for service with a front-line squadron. These OCUs utilize operational aircraft alongside advanced [simulators](/Flight_simulator) and rigorous ground training, though in the case of the Typhoon, a dedicated two-seater training variant, designated the Typhoon T3, also exists.

On 15 October 2020, it was announced that a joint RAF-Qatari Air Force Hawk squadron, mirroring the successful model of [No. 12 Squadron](/No._12_Squadron_RAF), would be formed in the future. Further details emerged on 1 April 2021, specifying that this squadron would be stood up in September 2021 at [RAF Leeming](/RAF_Leeming), North Yorkshire. The Joint Hawk Training Squadron received its first two Hawk Mk.167s at RAF Leeming on 1 September 2021. On 24 November 2021, this joint unit officially became [11 Squadron QEAF](/11_Squadron_(Qatar)) upon its reformation at RAF Leeming, solidifying the international partnership.

#### Multi-engine training

Multi-Engine aircrew, along with weapon systems officer (WSO) and weapon systems operator (WSOp) students, receive their training on the [Embraer Phenom T1](/Embraer_Phenom_100). This aircraft is operated by [No. 45 Squadron](/No._45_Squadron_RAF), based at [RAF Cranwell](/RAF_Cranwell). Upon completion of their multi-engine training, aircrew then proceed to their specific Operational Conversion Unit or directly to a front-line squadron, ready to apply their skills.

